@node features "Features"

                               Features

-Simple installation: just run the game and play!

-Aye_Q is a "Workbench" game, so it is meant to be played on the
 Workbench screen. The game window can be resized up to a maximum of
 640 x 400 pixels, and the game is redisplayed according to the new
 window size. If the window is too small, it will automatically be
 resized to an adequate displayable size.

-As the game uses as little of the computer's ressources as possible,
 you can run other applications, games, etc. at the same time.

-Aye_Q works on all Amigas with Workbench 1.3 or higher.

@endnode

@node histo "History"

                               Versions History

  What follows are the various updates that were done since the first
version of this game.

1.0:  First release.

1.01-1.12: It was so long ago... the earliest versions are more than
           10 years old (!). Unfortunately, I didn't fully kept track
           of the changes then... Let's just say that there were bug
           fixes and various code and cosmetic changes.

1.13: Some corrections to the game code: a bug caused the game to crash
      in some circumstances when the game window was resized.

1.14: No more blitting objects! Now the game draws 'pegs' and 'Empty
      spaces' with simple OS friendly commands (it is more usable for
      systems using Amiga emulators such as MorphOS, Amithlon, etc.).

1.2:  Test version (unreleased).

1.21: The pull-down menus were enhanced. Other improvements were made
      to the program code as well as various cosmetic changes.

1.22: -Bugfix: Sometimes, a peg that was clicked on remained 'pressed down'
       when the player clicked outside of the game board.
      -Some other changes were made to the program code.

1.23: -The starting position is now indicated by a coloured square.
      -The routine that generates the game window size has been revised.
      -Some additional changes have been made to the program code.

1.24: -The routine that checks if the game window is too small has been
       revised.
      -Various program code changes have been made.

@endnode

@node play "The game: Installation/Playing"

                             Installation

  The installation is very simple, just place "Aye_Q" where you want
on your hard drive, floppy disk, Ram Disk, etc. No other files or
Libraries are needed.

                             How to play?

  To move a peg (a tile with rectangular shape on it), you just click
on it with the mouse pointer and you click on the empty space (a tile
with a small dot) where you want to move the peg. You can only move a
peg 2 spaces horizontally or vertically. If the move is possible, the
selected peg will go there.

  In 'Aye_Q' there are two ways to play:

 -The @{b}Normal@{ub} game:   You must jump over a @{b}peg@{ub} and that peg will be
                     removed.

 -The @{b}Inverted@{ub} game: You must jump over an @{b}empty space@{ub} and a peg will
                     appear there, just as if you would play the 'Normal'
                     game backward.

  The goal of the game is to remove all the pegs (or fill up the board,
if the game is inverted), until only one peg is left (or only one space
is empty, in the inverted game), preferably in the center, where the empty
space (or peg) was at the start.

  When there are no possible moves, the game ends and Aye_Q will display
how many pegs (or empty spaces for the 'Inverted' game) are remaining.

  Have fun!

OPTIONS
-------

  At the right of the game board, the following buttons are shown:

 -@{b}New Game@{ub}:             Restarts the game.

 -@{b}About...@{ub}:             Displays the informations about the game.

 -@{b}Normal/Inverted Game@{ub}: This is a toggle button between the 'Normal'
                        and the 'Inverted' game.

@endnode

